  <TITLE> rectang  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE> May, 2006 </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="rectang"> create a rectangular aperture object. </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[aperture]=rectang(x_size, y_size)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>x_size  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the size of rectangular aperture in x direction. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME> y_size  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the size of rectangular aperture in y direction. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>aperture  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the rectangular aperture constructed. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    create a rectangular aperture object. 
    notice: it is't diffrent to rect_ap, because it does not include the process to filter the field.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
	number=256;
	wavelength=1e-6;
	pixscl=0.1;sz=number*pixscl;
	dwf=begin(sz,wavelength);
	ap=rectang(sz/2,sz/2);
	dwf=aperture_transform(dwf,ap);
	dwf_fits(dwf,"rect_ap");
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
